.SH "NAME"
Test::Stream::Plugin::Warnings \- Simple tools for testing code that may
generate warnings.
.SH "EXPERIMENTAL CODE WARNING"
.IX Header "EXPERIMENTAL CODE WARNING"
\&\fBThis is an experimental release!\fR Test-Stream, and all its components are
still in an experimental phase. This dist has been released to cpan in order to
allow testers and early adopters the chance to write experimental new tools
with it, or to add experimental support for it into old tools.
.PP
\&\fB\s-1PLEASE DO NOT COMPLETELY CONVERT OLD TOOLS YET\s0\fR. This experimental release is
very likely to see a lot of code churn. \s-1API\s0's may break at any time.
Test-Stream should \s-1NOT\s0 be depended on by any toolchain level tools until the
experimental phase is over.
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&    # Load the Warnings plugin, and More cause we need that as well.
\&    use Test::Stream qw/More Warnings/;
\&
\&    # Returns undef if there are no warnings.
\&    ok(!warns { ... }, "Codeblock did not warn");
\&
\&    is_deeply(
\&        warns { warn "foo\en"; warn "bar\en" },
\&        [
\&            "foo\en",
\&            "bar\en",
\&        ],
\&        "Got expected warnings"
\&    );
\&
\&    # Dies if there are 0 warnings, or 2+ warnings, otherwise returns the 1 warning.
\&    like( warning { warn \*(Aqxxx\*(Aq }, qr/xxx/, "Got expected warning");
.Ve
.SH "EXPORTS"
.IX Header "EXPORTS"
.ie n .IP "$warnings = warns { ... }" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$warnings\fR = warns { ... }" 4
.IX Item "$warnings = warns { ... }"
If the codeblock issues any warnings they will be captured and returned in an
arrayref. If there were no warnings this will return undef. You can be sure
this will always be undef, or an arrayref with 1 or more warnings.
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&    # Returns undef if there are no warnings.
\&    ok(!warns { ... }, "Codeblock did not warn");
\&
\&    is_deeply(
\&        warns { warn "foo\en"; warn "bar\en" },
\&        [
\&            "foo\en",
\&            "bar\en",
\&        ],
\&        "Got expected warnings"
\&    );
.Ve
.ie n .IP "$warning = warning { ... }" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$warning\fR = warning { ... }" 4
.IX Item "$warning = warning { ... }"
Only use this for code that should issue exactly 1 warning. This will throw an
exception if there are no warnings, or if there are multiple warnings.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    like( warning { warn \*(Aqxxx\*(Aq }, qr/xxx/, "Got expected warning");
.Ve
.Sp
These both die:
.Sp
.Vb 2
\&    warning { warn \*(Aqxxx\*(Aq; warn \*(Aqyyy\*(Aq };
\&    warning { return };
.Ve
.ie n .IP "$bool = no_warnings { ... }" 4
.el .IP "\f(CW$bool\fR = no_warnings { ... }" 4
.IX Item "$bool = no_warnings { ... }"
This will return true if there are no warnings in the codeblock. This will
return false, and print the warnings if any are encountered.
.Sp
.Vb 1
\&    ok(no_warnings { ... }, "Did not warn.");
.Ve
.Sp
This is sometimes more useful that checking \f(CW\*(C`!warns { ... }\*(C'\fR since it lets you
see the warnings when it fails.
